So Monday she went to school and her teacher called me in the middle of the afternoon.

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.150
She said, "Brandon, what did you do to Megan?

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.000
Something's happened.

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.100
" And I said, "Hold on, Kimberly.

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.400
What do you mean?

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.100
What did I do to Megan?

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.100
What do you mean what happened?

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.500
" and she said, "Explain to me how she's saying words.

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.450
" She said over 50 parroted words today.

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.100
We're talking a child that had no vocabulary at all, was not able to function at all, able to keep eye contact for the first time.

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.050
She made a list of all the words that Megan was saying on a piece of paper and we still have that today.

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.500
We still have it today because it was a miracle.

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.750
Megan still says things like parroting things all the time now and she says, "I love you," she says, "hi daddy," she says, "hi mommy.

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.450
" Those are the things Megan does now.

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.800
She's starting and it's becoming more and more every day—"I want food," "I want water"—things like that from nothing at all to now starting to say little phrases.

